² Dorubrevi] Probably the capital of a king of the West Kentings, Kemble, i. 148', as the seatsv of bishoprics were always fixed to the capitale of kingdoms. It is called Durobrivis by Antoninus, Durobra- bis by the Ravennese Geographer. But in the Tabula Peutingeriana (end of fourth century), we find it called Rotibis, and in the Textus Roffensis, ‘ Hrofbrevi, Civitas Roibi.’ Hrof or lirosa, therefore, must have been a chieftain in West Kent in the fourth century—possibly a Saxon who became more or less independent of the Roman dominion. Harpsfield asserts that in his time (sixteenth century) 13110 name was still common in Kent.

³ territoria] ‘ Priestfield, and all the land between the Medway and the east gate, to the north of the city (of Rochester).’ Emulfus‚ quoted in Wharton’s Ang. Sac. i. 333.

4 foras] ‘ Augustine the Roman fixed his burial-place by the side of the great Roman road, which then ran from Deal to Canterbury over St. Martin’s hill, and entered the town by the gateway which still marks the course of the old road.’ Stanley, p. 24.
